\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
A CI record is distinct from an asset record.
 A 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 asset record answers whether a physical asset exists,
 who owns it,
 where it is,
 and what its operational state is.
 A Policy 3.08 CI record answers what that asset's current configuration identity is,
 what its operational relationships are,
 and whether its record is complete and current.
 Both records co-exist in the System of Engagement and cross-reference each other via the Related Issues field,
 but they serve different governance purposes and neither substitutes for the other.
 An asset enters inventory under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 It becomes a CI under this policy at the time of deployment into the operational environment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Department treats CI record accuracy as an operational obligation,
 not an administrative one.
 A deployed asset with an incomplete or inaccurate CI record is not fully serviceable.
 This policy establishes the mechanisms by which that standard is maintained continuously.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Configuration Item Definition and Lifecycle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
A Configuration Item (CI) is any deployed IT asset whose configuration identity,
 operational relationships,
 and work order history require tracking to support service delivery,
 incident response,
 problem investigation,
 and change management.
 All Information Operations Personnel shall create a CI record in the System of Engagement at the time an asset is deployed into the operational environment.
 CI record creation shall not precede completion of supply chain review under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The assigned Information Operations Personnel shall ensure that the CI record cross-references the 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 asset record for the same physical asset via the Related Issues field in the System of Engagement.
 The assigned Information Operations Personnel shall retire the CI record when the asset is decommissioned under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 System of Record Architecture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department operates a two-layer configuration management architecture.
 Both layers are authoritative within their respective domains.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
System of Engagement (CI Identity and Inventory)
\series default
:
 The System of Engagement is the designated system of record for CI identity and inventory.
 It holds configuration identity,
 physical location,
 operational state,
 funding source,
 assigned user,
 network identifiers,
 work order linkage,
 and annual verification date.
 The System of Engagement is the authoritative record of what a deployed asset is and where it belongs within the County's operational environment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Endpoint Protection Platform (Active Configuration State)
\series default
:
 The Endpoint Protection Platform is the designated system of record for active endpoint configuration management.
 It holds OS version,
 patch level,
 software inventory,
 and endpoint compliance state.
 The Endpoint Protection Platform is the authoritative source for what a deployed asset is running.
 Reporting and compliance obligations for endpoint configuration state shall be satisfied by reference to Endpoint Protection Platform output.
 CI records in the System of Engagement shall not attempt to replicate Endpoint Protection Platform data,
 and population of CI fields shall not be used as a substitute for Endpoint Protection Platform compliance reporting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Active configuration compliance —
 including OS patch level and endpoint hardening state —
 is enforced through the Endpoint Protection Platform.
 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.10"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 defines the security baseline requirements that the Endpoint Protection Platform enforces.
 This policy does not restate those requirements and does not own baseline enforcement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 CI Minimum Field Set
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The following fields constitute a complete CI record in the System of Engagement and shall all be populated for any deployed asset.
 The obligation this policy establishes is population discipline —
 ensuring that these fields are populated accurately and kept current —
 not the creation of new fields beyond those defined here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Subject (Device Name / Asset Tag).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Status.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Location and Room Number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Date Received.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Equipment Type.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Manufacturer and Model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Serial Number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Assigned User (where applicable).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Device Name.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
IP Address (Ethernet and/or Wireless,
 where applicable).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
MAC Address (Ethernet and/or Wireless,
 where applicable).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Funding Source.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Expected Expiration Date.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Verified (annual audit date).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Related Issues (work order linkage).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All Information Operations Personnel shall populate network identity fields (IP Address and MAC Address) for all deployed networked assets.
 A deployed asset with Deployed status and empty network identity fields constitutes a record deficit requiring remediation.
 The IT Director shall approve any modification to the CI minimum field set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 CI Record Accuracy —
 Governing Principle and Work Order Closure Condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Department treats CI record deficits as operationally equivalent to functional deficits.
 A deployed asset with an incomplete or inaccurate CI record is not fully serviceable.
 A work order in which that asset is the primary subject of active work shall not be closed until the record deficit is remediated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The CI verification and remediation obligation applies when the asset is the primary subject of active work in the work order —
 the asset being repaired,
 configured,
 deployed,
 or serviced.
 This obligation shall be restricted to the primary CI;
 it shall not extend to assets mentioned incidentally in a work order where active work is being performed on a different asset.
 The annual physical audit defined in Section 6.5 is the systematic mechanism for identifying and remediating record deficits on assets not recently touched by a work order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The following mechanics govern CI record accuracy enforcement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The assigned technician shall verify that all required CI fields defined in Section 6.3 are populated as a condition of work order closure for any work order in which an asset is the primary subject.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
If the assigned technician discovers a record deficit during a work order,
 the assigned technician shall remediate the CI record before closing the work order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
If remediation requires information the assigned technician cannot obtain independently,
 the work order shall remain open until the information is obtained and the CI record is updated.
 The assigned technician shall not close a work order with a known CI deficit documented and deferred.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The assigned technician shall treat discovery of a CI record deficit during any work order as a defect requiring correction,
 not an observation to be deferred.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This obligation operates as a supplemental closure condition alongside the base work order closure standard defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
